article.headline: Mississippi State 89, New Orleans 63
article.story: JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Charles Rhodes' rehabilitation assignment appears to be over. The Mississippi State center may have a hard time fighting his way back into the starting lineup, however, if freshman Jarvis Varnado keeps playing the way he did Thursday in the Bulldogs' 89-63 win over New Orleans. Varnado had seven of the Bulldogs' team record 15 blocks. He also scored 13 points and gobbled up 15 rebounds, keying another strong defensive performance by Mississippi State. "It shocked me," Varnado said of New Orleans' constant attempts to drive the lane. "If they're going to go in amongst me, Charles and Vernon (Goodridge) then we're just going to keep sending it out." Those blocks led to plenty of easy transition baskets as the Bulldogs (9-2) simply ran away from the Privateers (5-7) for their seventh straight win. Mississippi State led 50-27 at halftime and slowly pulled away in the second half, leading by as much as 37. Rhodes scored 25 points off the bench, including a pair of 3-pointers, and blocked four shots. Goodridge and guard Reginald Delk added two blocks apiece. Except for the tape on his right wrist, there was little sign of the injury Rhodes has been nursing for weeks. He said he's not completely healed yet and has been playing at about 70 percent. But in front of his hometown crowd during the neutral-site game at Jackson's Mississippi Coliseum led to an amped-up performance. "My pride was 100 percent," Rhodes said. The steady dominance of Mississippi State's frontcourt was matched by the frenetic play of its backcourt. Jamont Gordon had the best game in the backcourt, scoring 19 points with six assists, including two passes on alley-oop dunks in transition. New Orleans coach Buzz Williams came away impressed. "They are a dominant team with really good players with a lot of depth and they are an NCAA tournament team with the possibility to do good things," Williams said. The Bulldogs held their opponent to less than 40 percent shooting for the ninth time in 11 games. They limited the Privateers to 31 percent shooting and held the nation's No. 3 scorer Bo McCalebb to 16 points, 10 below his average. Mississippi State was eighth in the nation and first in the Southeastern Conference in field-goal percentage defense coming into the game, allowing opponents to hit 35 percent of their shots, and only improved on its numbers. The Bulldogs allowed the Privateers just six second-chance points, held a rebound advantage of 47-31 and outscored them 44-20 in the paint. The game was well out of reach by halftime after Mississippi State built a 50-27 lead. They led by as much as 37 late. Shaun Reynolds had 17 for New Orleans and Jamie McNeilly added 13. "Obviously, I'm happy with the win," Mississippi State coach Rick Stansbury said. "But more importantly, I am happy with the way we got the win."
